<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE MAJOR LEAGUES; INDIANS ACQUIRE RUSSELL FROM 
RED SOX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Boston Red Sox traded slumping relief pitcher Jeff Russell to the 
Cleveland Indians for pitchers Chris Nabholz and Steve Farr. 
</P>
<P>
 Russell (0-5), who gave up one run and three hits while pitching the ninth 
inning of Boston's 6-3 loss to the Oakland Athletics on Friday, has 12 saves in 
15 opportunities this season with a 5.14 earned-run average. 
</P>
<P>
 He got his fifth loss Wednesday when he gave up a 10th-inning homer to Danny 
Tartabull in a 4-3 loss to the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
 Nabholz, a left-hander who was 3-1 on a rehabilitation assignment with 
triple-A Charlotte while recovering from a strained upper back, is scheduled to 
start Sunday for the Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
 Farr, a right-handed reliever who is on the disabled list because of a stiff 
neck, is expected to be ready to pitch for Boston on July 10. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Red Sox Manager Butch Hobson, already under fire for his club's recent woes, 
was suspended for five games for shoving an umpire. Hobson has appealed the 
decision by American League President Bobby Brown. A hearing is pending. . . . 
Houston Astro General Manager Bob Watson, 48, announced that he has prostate 
cancer and will have the gland removed Wednesday in St. Louis. He will be 
hospitalized for five days, then return to Houston to recuperate. Watson is 
expected to resume a limited work schedule after a recovery period estimated at 
30 days. . . . Chicago Cub announcer Harry Caray remained hospitalized for 
treatment of a rapid heart beat. Caray, 77, was admitted to Northwestern 
Memorial in Chicago last Saturday after being discharged three days earlier 
from a Florida hospital, where he was taken after he fell while leaving a 
dugout at Miami's Joe Robbie Stadium. 
</P>
