<P>
OFF THE TICKER: DOES IT COUNT IF THEY'RE GAP JEANS? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For U.S. firms wondering how to keep workers happy, a study offers this 
advice: Let them wear jeans. 
</P>
<P>
 The nationwide survey of white-collar workers found that 81% agree that 
allowing casual dress improves morale and 47% believe it improves productivity. 
</P>
<P>
 Almost all respondents, 96%, said they dress casually when they can. 
Eighty-four percent said jeans were acceptable in their offices. Asked if a 
casual dress policy could influence their decision in accepting a job offer, 
46% said it would. 
</P>
<P>
 The source of this wisdom? A telephone survey of 750 employees, commissioned 
by Levi Strauss & Co. 
</P>
